---
import LocationLayout from '../../layouts/LocationLayout.astro';
import { marsLocations } from '../../data/marsLocations';

const location = marsLocations.find(loc => loc.id === 'ares-vallis');
if (!location) {
  throw new Error('Ares Vallis location not found');
}
---

<LocationLayout title="Ares Vallis - Mars Location" location={location}>
  <!-- Hero Image Section -->
  <div class="mb-8">
    <div
      class="relative h-96 bg-gradient-to-r from-red-900 to-orange-700 rounded-lg overflow-hidden"
    >
      <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-black/20"></div>
      <div class="absolute bottom-6 left-6 text-white">
        <p class="text-sm opacity-80">
          Mars Pathfinder lander and Sojourner rover in the Ares Vallis flood plains
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs opacity-60">NASA/JPL</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Overview Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Overview</h2>
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Ares Vallis stands as a monument to Mars' catastrophically violent
          water-dominated past, serving as the historic landing site for NASA's
          groundbreaking Mars Pathfinder mission and humanity's first successful
          Mars rover, Sojourner. This massive ancient flood channel, named after
          Ares, the Greek god of war, stretches over 1,757 kilometers across the
          Martian landscape, carved by some of the largest floods ever recorded
          in the solar system.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          The flood plains of Ares Vallis tell the story of catastrophic water
          release events that occurred billions of years ago when Mars had a
          thicker atmosphere and warmer climate. These massive floods transported
          rocks from diverse regions across Mars, creating a natural rock
          collection that provided scientists with their first detailed analysis
          of Martian geology from the surface.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          The successful Pathfinder mission in 1997 not only marked humanity's
          return to the Martian surface after the Viking missions but also
          demonstrated innovative landing technologies and proved that relatively
          low-cost missions could achieve groundbreaking scientific discoveries,
          paving the way for all subsequent Mars exploration.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Quick Facts Sidebar -->
      <div class="bg-gray-800/50 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">Quick Facts</h3>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Channel Length:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">1,757 km</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Formation:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">Catastrophic flooding</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Historic Mission:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">Mars Pathfinder (1997)</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">First Rover:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">Sojourner (12 weeks)</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Key Discovery:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">Andesitic rocks and water evidence</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Pathfinder Mission Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Mars Pathfinder: Pioneering Modern Mars Exploration
    </h2>
    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-8 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        Launched on December 4, 1996, Mars Pathfinder revolutionized Mars
        exploration by demonstrating that innovative, cost-effective missions
        could achieve remarkable scientific results. The mission landed in Ares
        Vallis on July 4, 1997, using a pioneering airbag landing system that
        allowed the spacecraft to bounce to a safe landing on the rocky terrain.
      </p>
      
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Mission Innovations</h4>
          <ul class="text-gray-300 text-sm space-y-2">
            <li>• First airbag landing system on Mars</li>
            <li>• Cost-effective "faster, better, cheaper" approach</li>
            <li>• Real-time internet coverage of landing</li>
            <li>• Deployed first successful Mars rover</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Scientific Objectives</h4>
          <ul class="text-gray-300 text-sm space-y-2">
            <li>• Characterize Martian rocks and soil</li>
            <li>• Study atmospheric conditions</li>
            <li>• Test mobile rover technology</li>
            <li>• Analyze flood deposit geology</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-blue-900/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-blue-700/50">
        <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Sojourner Rover Achievements</h4>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          The 23-pound Sojourner rover, originally designed for a 7-day mission,
          operated successfully for 12 weeks, far exceeding expectations. This
          pioneering rover analyzed 16 different rocks using its Alpha Proton
          X-ray Spectrometer (APXS) and took over 550 images of the Martian
          landscape.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          Sojourner's success proved that robotic exploration could provide
          detailed scientific analysis while being mobile enough to investigate
          multiple targets, establishing the foundation for all future Mars
          rover missions including Spirit, Opportunity, Curiosity, and
          Perseverance.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Flood Channel Geology Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Catastrophic Flood Channel: Ancient Water's Violent Past
    </h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-8">
      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-blue-900/50 to-blue-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-blue-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Formation by Megafloods
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          Ares Vallis was carved by catastrophic floods that rivaled or exceeded
          the largest floods known on Earth. These massive water releases
          occurred when underground aquifers burst forth, creating flood
          volumes that could have filled the Mediterranean Sea in a matter
          of days.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          The floods originated from chaotic terrain regions far to the south,
          where massive groundwater release events carved the distinctive
          channels that flow through Xanthe Terra highlands before ending
          in the Chryse Planitia delta region.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-orange-900/50 to-orange-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-orange-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Rock Transport and Deposition
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          The catastrophic floods transported rocks from diverse geological
          regions across hundreds of kilometers, creating a natural
          "rock collection" in the Ares Vallis flood plains. This transport
          process deposited rocks with different compositions and histories
          in a single location.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          The flood deposits include everything from ancient crater materials
          to volcanic rocks, providing a unique opportunity to study Mars'
          geological diversity without traveling vast distances across the
          planet's surface.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
        Scale and Timing of Ancient Floods
      </h3>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        The floods that carved Ares Vallis occurred during Mars' early history
        when the planet had a thicker atmosphere and warmer climate conditions.
        These events represent some of the most dramatic water-related geological
        processes ever documented in the solar system, with flow rates that
        may have exceeded 10 million cubic meters per second.
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
        The timing of these floods corresponds to a period when Mars was
        transitioning from its early, more Earth-like conditions to the cold,
        arid planet we observe today, making Ares Vallis a crucial record of
        this dramatic climate change.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Rock Analysis and Discoveries Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Groundbreaking Rock Analysis and Water Evidence
    </h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-8">
      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-green-900/50 to-green-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-green-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          "Barnacle Bill" and Andesitic Composition
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          Sojourner's analysis of "Barnacle Bill," the first rock studied on
          Mars, revealed an andesitic composition with higher silica content
          than expected. This discovery was significant because andesites
          typically form through complex geological processes involving
          crust-mantle interactions.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          The presence of andesitic rocks suggested that early Mars had more
          complex geological processes than previously thought, including
          potentially active plate tectonics or extensive crustal recycling
          processes that concentrated silica-rich materials.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-purple-900/50 to-purple-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-purple-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Water-Worked Conglomerates
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          The most exciting discoveries were rounded pebbles and conglomerate
          rocks that clearly showed evidence of water transport and deposition.
          These features indicated that liquid water had flowed through the
          region, rounding and cementing different rock types together.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          The presence of these water-worked features provided direct evidence
          for Mars' wetter past and supported theories about catastrophic
          flooding events. The conglomerates showed that water persisted
          long enough to perform significant geological work.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
        Diverse Rock Collection Analysis
      </h3>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Sojourner analyzed 16 different rocks during its extended mission,
        revealing a remarkable diversity of compositions that told the story
        of Mars' geological evolution. The rocks ranged from basaltic volcanic
        materials to more evolved silica-rich compositions, indicating complex
        magmatic processes.
      </p>
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 mt-4">
        <div class="text-center">
          <h5 class="text-white font-semibold mb-2">Volcanic Rocks</h5>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">Basaltic to andesitic compositions indicating diverse magmatic processes</p>
        </div>
        <div class="text-center">
          <h5 class="text-white font-semibold mb-2">Sedimentary Features</h5>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">Rounded pebbles and conglomerate rocks from water transport</p>
        </div>
        <div class="text-center">
          <h5 class="text-white font-semibold mb-2">Impact Materials</h5>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">Rocks likely derived from ancient impact crater formations</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Modern Understanding Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Modern Understanding and Recent Insights
    </h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-8">
      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-red-900/50 to-red-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-red-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Enhanced Orbital Perspectives (2024)
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          Recent high-resolution imagery and analysis continue to reveal new
          details about the ancient flood processes that shaped Ares Vallis.
          ESA's Mars Express mission has provided detailed fly-around
          perspectives showing the dramatic scale of the ancient flooding.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          The 2024 imagery reveals that the flood channels extend even further
          than originally mapped, with evidence for multiple flood episodes
          that occurred over extended periods, suggesting that water activity
          in this region was more sustained than initially thought.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-teal-900/50 to-teal-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-teal-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Comparative Planetary Geology
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          Studies of Ares Vallis have become crucial for understanding
          catastrophic flooding processes throughout the solar system. The
          channel's features are now used as analogs for similar processes
          on other planets and moons where water or other fluids may have
          carved surface features.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          The geological processes documented at Ares Vallis help scientists
          understand how catastrophic fluid release events can rapidly reshape
          planetary surfaces, providing insights relevant to astrobiology
          and planetary evolution studies.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
        Climate Evolution Implications
      </h3>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Modern analysis of Pathfinder data, combined with results from
        subsequent missions, has refined our understanding of Mars' climate
        evolution. The evidence from Ares Vallis supports models suggesting
        that early Mars experienced episodic warm periods when large volumes
        of liquid water could flow across the surface.
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
        The geological record preserved in Ares Vallis indicates that these
        warm, wet periods may have been relatively brief in geological terms
        but intense enough to carve massive channel systems and transport
        enormous volumes of rock and sediment across the planet.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Terraforming Potential Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Terraforming Assessment
    </h2>
    <div
      class="bg-gradient-to-br from-orange-900/30 to-orange-800/20 p-8 rounded-lg border border-orange-700/50"
    >
      <div class="flex items-center mb-6">
        <div
          class="w-12 h-12 bg-orange-600 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center mr-4"
        >
          <span class="text-white font-bold text-xl">6</span>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white">
            Moderate Terraforming Potential
          </h3>
          <p class="text-orange-300">
            Diverse geological resources and historical significance
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Advantages</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Diverse rock samples from across Mars</li>
            <li>• Proven ancient water flow evidence</li>
            <li>• Relatively flat terrain for construction</li>
            <li>• Extensive geological diversity</li>
            <li>• Historical significance for Mars exploration</li>
            <li>• Well-characterized landing site</li>
            <li>• Access to flood channel deposits</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Challenges</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Limited current water resources</li>
            <li>• Ancient age of water activity</li>
            <li>• Dust accumulation issues</li>
            <li>• Radiation exposure on open plains</li>
            <li>• Distance from polar ice caps</li>
            <li>• Moderate elevation with temperature extremes</li>
            <li>• Limited subsurface resource data</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Scientific Legacy Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Scientific Legacy and Impact
    </h2>
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Foundation of Modern Mars Exploration
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          The Mars Pathfinder mission at Ares Vallis established the template
          for all subsequent Mars exploration. Its innovative landing system,
          cost-effective approach, and successful rover deployment proved that
          ambitious scientific objectives could be achieved with relatively
          modest budgets, leading to the golden age of Mars exploration.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Water Activity Evidence
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          Ares Vallis provided some of the first definitive surface evidence
          for ancient water activity on Mars through analysis of rounded
          pebbles and conglomerate rocks. This evidence helped establish the
          scientific foundation for understanding Mars as a planet that once
          had conditions potentially suitable for life.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Geological Diversity Insights
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          The diverse collection of rocks deposited by ancient floods in Ares
          Vallis provided scientists with insights into Mars' geological
          complexity that would have required multiple landing sites to obtain
          otherwise. This "natural rock collection" revealed the planet's
          varied geological processes and compositional evolution.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Future Research Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Future Research Opportunities
    </h2>
    <div
      class="bg-gradient-to-br from-purple-900/30 to-purple-800/20 p-8 rounded-lg border border-purple-700/50"
    >
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        While Ares Vallis has been extensively studied since the Pathfinder
        mission, modern analytical techniques and advanced rover capabilities
        could reveal new insights about this historically significant location.
        The channel system continues to be an important target for understanding
        Mars' hydrological history and climate evolution.
      </p>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">
            Advanced Analysis Opportunities
          </h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• High-resolution mineralogical mapping</li>
            <li>• Subsurface water/ice resource assessment</li>
            <li>• Advanced organic compound detection</li>
            <li>• Detailed flood chronology studies</li>
            <li>• Comparative analysis with other flood channels</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">
            Historical Preservation Value
          </h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Pathfinder landing site preservation</li>
            <li>• Educational and inspirational significance</li>
            <li>• Comparison with modern rover capabilities</li>
            <li>• Benchmark location for technological advancement</li>
            <li>• Cultural heritage site for space exploration</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- External Resources Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Learn More</h2>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">NASA Resources</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://science.nasa.gov/mission/mars-pathfinder/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Mars Pathfinder Mission Overview
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://mars.nasa.gov/mars-exploration/missions/pathfinder/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Mars Exploration: Pathfinder
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.space.com/17745-mars-pathfinder-sojourner-rover.html"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Sojourner: First Mars Rover
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">Scientific Resources</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.esa.int/ESA_Multimedia/Videos/2024/11/Fly_around_Ares_Vallis_on_Mars"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              ESA: Ares Vallis Fly-Around (2024)
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://themis.asu.edu/feature/20"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              THEMIS: Geological Footprints
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ares_Vallis"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Ares Vallis Overview
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</LocationLayout>